\mathrm{SNR} \equiv 10 \log \left[\frac{\text{signal power}}{\text{noise power}}\right] \mathrm{dB} \tag{9.5}
\end{equation*}
$$

Therefore, if a node in a circuit comprises a signal, $\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{x}}(\mathrm{t})$, with a normalized signal power of $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{x}(\mathrm{ms})}^{2}$ and a normalized noise power of $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n}(\mathrm{ms})}^{2}$, the SNR can be expressed as

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{SNR}=10 \log \left[\frac{\mathrm{~V}_{\mathrm{x}(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}}{\mathrm{~V}_{\mathrm{n}(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}}\right]=20 \log \left[\frac{\mathrm{~V}_{\mathrm{x}(\mathrm{rms})}}{\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n}(\mathrm{~ms})}}\right] \mathrm{dB} \tag{9.6}
\end{equation*}
$$

Key Point: SNR represents the ratio of signal power to noise power, both normalized to identical impedance and articulated in dB.

Obviously, when the mean-squared values of the noise and signal are identical, $\mathrm{SNR}=0 \mathrm{~dB}$.

Even though dB units represent the relative ratio between two power levels, it is often beneficial to understand a signal's power in dB on an absolute scale. A widely used measure is dBm, where all power levels are referenced to 1 mW. In simpler terms, a 1-mW signal equates to 0 dBm, while a $1-\mu \mathrm{W}$ signal equates to -30 dBm. When measuring voltage levels, it is also standard to reference the voltage to the equivalent power dissipated if the voltage is applied across either a $50-\Omega$ or a $75-\Omega$ resistor.

Key Point: dBm units represent an average power level on a logarithmic scale normalized to 1 mW, so 1 mW equals 0 dBm and 0.1 mW equals -10 dBm. RMS voltages or currents are occasionally expressed in dBm by assuming they are applied to a predefined reference load, typically either 50 or 75 Ohms.

#### EXAMPLE 9.1

Determine the rms voltage of a $0-\mathrm{dBm}$ signal referenced to a $50-\Omega$ resistor. What is the dBm level of a 2-volt rms signal?

#### Solution

A $0-\mathrm{dBm}$ signal referenced to a $50-\Omega$ resistor indicates that the rms voltage level is

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{V}_{(\mathrm{rms})}=\sqrt{(50 \Omega) \times 1 \mathrm{~mW}}=0.2236 \mathrm{~V} \tag{9.7}
\end{equation*}
$$

Therefore, a 2-volt rms signal corresponds to

$$
\begin{equation*}
20 \log \left(\frac{2.0}{0.2236}\right)=19 \mathrm{dBm} \tag{9.8}
\end{equation*}
$$

and would dissipate 80 mW across a $50-\Omega$ resistor.

It is important to note that the measured voltage may not actually be applied across any $50-\Omega$ resistor. The measured voltage is only referenced to power levels that would be expected if the voltage were applied to such a load. Similar outcomes are achieved if the power is referenced to a $75-\Omega$ resistor.

