Consider the scenario where two noise sources are combined, as depicted in Fig. 9.2. If the rms values of each individual noise source are known, what can be inferred about the rms value of the resultant signal? We address this query as follows. Let $\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{no}}(\mathrm{t})$ be defined as

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 0}(\mathrm{t})=\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 1}(\mathrm{t})+\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 2}(\mathrm{t}) \tag{9.9}
\end{equation*}
$$

where $\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 1}(\mathrm{t})$ and $\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 2}(\mathrm{t})$ are two noise sources with known rms values $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{~ms})}$ and $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{~ms})}$, respectively. Then, we can express

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{no}(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}=\frac{1}{\mathrm{~T}} \int_{0}^{\mathrm{T}}\left[\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 1}(\mathrm{t})+\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 2}(\mathrm{t})\right]^{2} \mathrm{dt} \tag{9.10}
\end{equation*}
$$

which, upon expansion, yields

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{no}(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}=\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}+\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}+\frac{2}{\mathrm{~T}} \int_{0}^{\mathrm{T}} \mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 1}(\mathrm{t}) \mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 2}(\mathrm{t}) \mathrm{dt} \tag{9.11}
\end{equation*}
$$

Note that the first two terms on the right-hand side of (9.11) represent the individual mean-squared values of the noise sources. The last term indicates the correlation between the two signal sources, $\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 1}(\mathrm{t})$ and $\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 2}(\mathrm{t})$. An alternative way to rewrite (9.11) that better highlights the effects of signal correlation is to define a correlation coefficient, C, as

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{C} \equiv \frac{\frac{1}{\mathrm{~T}} \int_{0}^{\mathrm{T}} \mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 1}(\mathrm{t}) \mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 2}(\mathrm{t}) \mathrm{dt}}{\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{rms})} \mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{rms})}} \tag{9.12}
\end{equation*}
$$

With this definition, (9.11) can also be expressed as

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{no}(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}=\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}+\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}+2 \mathrm{C} \mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{rms})} \mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{rms})} \tag{9.13}
\end{equation*}
$$

It can be demonstrated that the correlation coefficient always satisfies the condition $-1 \leq \mathrm{C} \leq 1$. Additionally, a value of $\mathrm{C} = \pm 1$ indicates that the two signals are fully correlated, while $\mathrm{C} = 0$ signifies that the signals are uncorrelated. Intermediate values imply partial correlation. Fortunately, there is seldom a need to analyze partially correlated signals since different inherent noise sources are typically uncorrelated.

For two uncorrelated signals, the mean-squared value of their sum is given by

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{no}(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}=\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}+\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{rms})}^{2} \tag{9.14}
\end{equation*}
$$

Key Point: The power of independent (uncorrelated) noise sources adds linearly, meaning their voltages and currents combine in a root-sum-of-squares manner. Consequently, to reduce overall noise, focus should be on the largest noise contributors.

This relationship suggests that when signals are uncorrelated, their rms values add as if they were the magnitudes of vectors at right angles to each other (i.e., orthogonal).

It is instructive to compare this uncorrelated scenario with the case of fully correlated signals. An example of two fully correlated (though deterministic) sources are two sinusoidal signals with the same frequency and a phase difference of 0 or 180 degrees. In this fully correlated case, the mean-squared value of their sum is given by

