#### EXAMPLE 9.2

Given two uncorrelated noise sources with $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{rms})}=10 \mu \mathrm{V}$ and $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{rms})}=5 \mu \mathrm{V}$, determine their combined output rms value. If the total rms value must be maintained at $10 \mu \mathrm{V}$, by how much should $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{rms})}$ be reduced while keeping $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{rms})}$ constant?

#### Solution

Using (9.14), we get

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{no}(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}=\left(10^{2}+5^{2}\right)=125(\mu \mathrm{V})^{2} \tag{9.16}
\end{equation*}
$$

which results in $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{no}(\mathrm{rms})}=11.2 \mu \mathrm{V}$. To maintain $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{no}(\mathrm{rms})}=10 \mu \mathrm{V}$ with $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{rms})}=5 \mu \mathrm{V}$, we have

$$
\begin{equation*}
10^{2}=\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}+5^{2} \tag{9.17}
\end{equation*}
$$

which yields $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{rms})}=8.7 \mu \mathrm{V}$. Thus, reducing $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{rms})}$ by 13 percent is equivalent to completely eliminating $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{rms})}$!

