V_{\mathrm{no}(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}=\left[\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{rms})} \pm \mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{rms})}\right]^{2} \tag{9.15}
\end{equation*}
$$

where the sign depends on whether the signals are in or out of phase. Note that in this fully correlated case, the rms values add linearly (similar to the magnitudes of aligned vectors).

#### EXAMPLE 9.2

Given two uncorrelated noise sources with $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{~ms})}=10 \mu \mathrm{~V}$ and $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{~ms})}=5 \mu \mathrm{~V}$, determine their combined output rms value. If the total rms value must be maintained at $10 \mu \mathrm{~V}$, by how much should $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n1}(\mathrm{rms})}$ be reduced while keeping $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{~ms})}$ constant?

#### Solution

Using (9.14), we find

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{no}(\mathrm{mss})}^{2}=\left(10^{2}+5^{2}\right)=125(\mu \mathrm{~V})^{2} \tag{9.16}
\end{equation*}
$$

which results in $\mathrm{V}_{\text {no(rms) }}=11.2 \mu \mathrm{~V}$. To maintain $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{no}(\mathrm{ms})}=10 \mu \mathrm{~V}$ with $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{rms})}=5 \mu \mathrm{~V}$, we have

$$
\begin{equation*}
10^{2}=V_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{~ms})}^{2}+5^{2} \tag{9.17}
\end{equation*}
$$

yielding $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{rms})}=8.7 \mu \mathrm{~V}$. Thus, reducing $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n1}(\mathrm{rms})}$ by 13 percent is equivalent to eliminating $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2 \text { (rms) }}$ entirely!

This example underscores a crucial principle: To minimize overall noise, focus on reducing large noise signals.

Consider the scenario where two noise sources are combined, as depicted in Fig. 9.2. If the rms values of each individual noise source are known, what can be inferred about the rms value of the resultant signal? We address this query as follows. Let $\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{no}}(\mathrm{t})$ be defined as

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 0}(\mathrm{t})=\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 1}(\mathrm{t})+\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 2}(\mathrm{t}) \tag{9.9}
\end{equation*}
$$

where $\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 1}(\mathrm{t})$ and $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2}(\mathrm{t})$ are two noise sources with known rms values $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{~ms})}$ and $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{~ms})}$, respectively. Then, we can express

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{no}(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}=\frac{1}{\mathrm{~T}} \int_{0}^{\mathrm{T}}\left[\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 1}(\mathrm{t})+\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2}(\mathrm{t})\right]^{2} \mathrm{dt} \tag{9.10}
\end{equation*}
$$

which, upon expansion, yields

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{no}(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}=\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}+\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}+\frac{2}{\mathrm{~T}} \int_{0}^{\mathrm{T}} \mathrm{~V}_{\mathrm{n} 1}(\mathrm{t}) \mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2}(\mathrm{t}) \mathrm{dt} \tag{9.11}
\end{equation*}
$$

Note that the first two terms on the right-hand side of (9.11) represent the individual mean-squared values of the noise sources. The last term indicates the correlation between the two signal sources, $\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 1}(\mathrm{t})$ and $\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 2}(\mathrm{t})$. An alternative way to express (9.11), which highlights the effects of signal correlation, is to define a correlation coefficient, C, as

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{C} \equiv \frac{\frac{1}{\mathrm{~T}} \int_{0}^{T} \mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{n} 1}(\mathrm{t}) \mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2}(\mathrm{t}) \mathrm{dt}}{\mathrm{~V}_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{rms})} \mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{rms})}} \tag{9.12}
\end{equation*}
$$

With this definition, (9.11) can also be written as

$$
\begin{equation*}
V_{\mathrm{no}(\mathrm{~ms})}^{2}=\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{~ms})}^{2}+\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}+2 C V_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{rms})} \mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{rms})} \tag{9.13}
\end{equation*}
$$

It can be demonstrated that the correlation coefficient always satisfies the condition $-1 \leq C \leq 1$. Additionally, a value of $C= \pm 1$ indicates that the two signals are fully correlated, while $\mathrm{C}=0$ signifies that the signals are uncorrelated. Intermediate values imply partial correlation. Fortunately, there is seldom a need to analyze partially correlated signals since different inherent noise sources are typically uncorrelated.

For two uncorrelated signals, the mean-squared value of their sum is given by

$$
\begin{equation*}
V_{\mathrm{no}(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}=V_{\mathrm{n} 1(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}+V_{\mathrm{n} 2(\mathrm{rms})}^{2} \tag{9.14}
\end{equation*}
$$

Key Point: The power of independent (uncorrelated) noise sources combines linearly, meaning their voltages and currents combine in a root-sum-of-squares manner. Consequently, to reduce overall noise, one should focus on the largest noise contributors.

This relationship suggests that two rms values add as if they were the magnitudes of vectors at right angles (i.e., orthogonal) when the signals are uncorrelated.

