We observed that the spectral density function is defined by the noise power within each 1-Hz bandwidth. Therefore, theoretically, one could measure the spectral density function by filtering a noise signal with a brick-wall bandpass filter that has a 1-Hz bandwidth. The term "brick wall" here indicates that the 1-Hz bandwidth of the filter is transmitted with a gain of one, while all other frequencies are completely eliminated. However, practical filters can only approximate a brick-wall response as their complexity (i.e., filter order) increases. Consequently, for lower-order filters with a 1-Hz passband, more noise power is transmitted than what is present in just a 1-Hz bandwidth. To address the fact that practical filters have more gradual stopband characteristics, the concept of noise bandwidth is introduced. The noise bandwidth of a given filter is equivalent to the frequency span of a brick-wall filter that produces the same rms output noise as the given filter when white noise is applied to both, assuming the same peak gain for both filters.

Key Point: The noise bandwidth of a specific filter is the frequency range of a brick-wall filter that yields the same rms output noise as the specific filter when white noise is applied, given the same peak gain for both filters.

For instance, consider a first-order, low-pass response with a 3-dB bandwidth of \( f_0 \), as depicted in Fig. 9.9(a). Such a response would arise from the RC filter shown in Fig. 9.8(b) with \( f_0 = (1 / 2 \pi R C) \). The transfer function \( A(s) \) is given by

$$
\begin{equation*}
A(s) = \frac{1}{1 + \frac{s}{2 \pi f_0}} \tag{9.33}
\end{equation*}
$$

This results in the magnitude response of \( A(s) \) being

$$
\begin{equation*}
|\mathrm{A}(\mathrm{j} 2 \pi \mathrm{f})| = \left(\frac{1}{1 + \left(\frac{\mathrm{f}}{\mathrm{f}_0}\right)^2}\right)^{1/2} \tag{9.34}
\end{equation*}
$$

An input signal, \( \mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{ni}}(\mathrm{f}) \), is a white noise source defined by

$$
\begin{equation*}
V_{n i}(f) = V_{n w} \tag{9.35}
\end{equation*}
$$

where \( V_{n w} \) is a constant. The total output noise rms value \( V_{n o}(f) \) is

$$
\begin{equation*}
V_{\mathrm{no}(\mathrm{rms})}^2 = \int_{0}^{\infty} \frac{\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{nw}}^2}{1 + \left(\frac{f}{f_0}\right)^2} \mathrm{df} = \left.\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{nw}}^2 \mathrm{f}_0 \arctan \left(\frac{\mathrm{f}}{\mathrm{f}_0}\right)\right|_{0}^{\infty} = \frac{\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{nw}}^2 \pi f_0}{2} \tag{9.36}
\end{equation*}
$$

If this same input signal, \( \mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{ni}}(\mathrm{f}) \), is applied to the filter shown in Fig. 9.9(b), the total output noise rms value becomes

$$
\begin{equation*}
V_{\text{brick(rms)}}^2 = \int_{0}^{f_x} V_{n w}^2 \mathrm{df} = V_{n w}^2 f_x \tag{9.37}
\end{equation*}
$$

By equating the two output noise rms values, \( \mathrm{V}_{\text{no(rms)}} = \mathrm{V}_{\text{brick(rms)}} \), we get

$$
\begin{equation*}
f_x = \frac{\pi f_0}{2} \tag{9.38}
\end{equation*}
$$

Thus, the noise bandwidth of a first-order, low-pass filter with a 3-dB bandwidth of \( f_0 \) is \( \pi(f_0 / 2) \). Note that, in the common case where a first-order circuit is realized by a capacitor \( C \) and the resistance \( R_{\text{eq}} \) seen by that capacitor, then

$$
\begin{equation*}
f_0 = \frac{1}{2 \pi R_{\text{eq}} C} \tag{9.39}
\end{equation*}
$$

and the noise bandwidth is

$$
\begin{equation*}
f_x = \frac{1}{4 R_{\text{eq}} C} \tag{9.40}
\end{equation*}
$$

The benefit of knowing the noise bandwidth of a filter is that, when white noise is applied to the filter input, the total output noise mean-squared value can be easily calculated by multiplying the spectral density by the noise bandwidth. Specifically, in the first-order case described, the total output noise mean-squared value, \( V_{\text{no(rms)}}^2 \), is

$$
\begin{equation*}
V_{\mathrm{no}(\mathrm{ms})}^2 = V_{\mathrm{nw}}^2 f_x = V_{\mathrm{nw}}^2 \left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right) f_0 \tag{9.41}
\end{equation*}
$$

Similar noise bandwidth relationships can be derived for higher-order and bandpass filters.

