The primary source of noise in resistors is thermal noise. As previously mentioned, it manifests as white noise and can be represented as a voltage source, $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{R}}(\mathrm{f})$, in series with a noiseless resistor. Using this method, the spectral density function, $V_{R}^{2}(f)$, is determined to be

$$
\begin{equation*}
V_{R}^{2}(f)=4 k T R \tag{9.47}
\end{equation*}
$$

where k is Boltzmann's constant $\left(1.38 \times 10^{-23} \mathrm{JK}^{-1}\right)$, T is the temperature in Kelvins, and R is the resistance value. Alternatively, equation (9.47) can be rephrased to note that a $1-\mathrm{k} \Omega$ resistor has a root spectral density of $4.06 \mathrm{nV} / \sqrt{\mathrm{Hz}}$ for thermal noise at room temperature $\left(300^{\circ} \mathrm{K}\right)$. Since the root spectral density is proportional to the square root of the resistance, it can also be expressed as

$$
\begin{equation*}
V_{R}(f)=\sqrt{\frac{R}{1 k}} \times 4.06 \mathrm{nV} / \sqrt{\mathrm{Hz}} \quad \text { for } 27^{\circ} \mathrm{C} \tag{9.48}
\end{equation*}
$$

Key Point: Thermal noise in resistors can be modeled either by a voltage source in series with the resistor having a spectral density of 4 kTR, or by a Norton equivalent current source with a spectral density of 4kT/R.

To decrease the thermal noise voltage from resistors, one must either reduce the temperature or use lower resistance values. The relationship between lower resistance values and reduced thermal noise becomes more evident when examining $\mathrm{kT} / \mathrm{C}$ noise in capacitors, as discussed later in this section.

An alternative model can be derived by determining the Norton equivalent circuit. Specifically, the series voltage noise source, $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{R}}(\mathrm{f})$, can be substituted with a parallel current noise source, $\mathrm{I}_{\mathrm{R}}(\mathrm{f})$, defined by

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{R}^{2}(f)=\frac{V_{R}^{2}(f)}{R^{2}}=\frac{4 k T}{R} \tag{9.49}
\end{equation*}
$$

Both resistor models are summarized in Fig. 9.11.

