The noise in bipolar transistors arises from the shot noise of both the collector and base currents, the flicker noise of the base current, and the thermal noise of the base resistance. It is customary to consolidate these various noise sources into two equivalent noise sources at the transistor's base, as depicted in Fig. 9.11. In this context, the equivalent input voltage noise, $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{i}}(\mathrm{f})$, is expressed as

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{i}}^{2}(\mathrm{f})=4 \mathrm{kT}\left(\mathrm{r}_{\mathrm{b}}+\frac{1}{2 \mathrm{~g}_{\mathrm{m}}}\right) \tag{9.52}
\end{equation*}
$$

Here, the $r_{b}$ term stems from the thermal noise of the base resistance, while the $g_{m}$ term originates from the collector-current shot noise referred to the input. The equivalent input current noise, $I_{i}(f)$, is given by

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{i}^{2}(f)=2 q\left(I_{B}+\frac{K I_{B}}{f}+\frac{I_{C}}{|\beta(f)|^{2}}\right) \tag{9.53}
\end{equation*}
$$

Key Point: Bipolar transistor noise is generally dominated by the thermal noise of the series base resistance and the shot noise in the base current junction.
In this equation, the $2 q I_{B}$ term represents base-current shot noise, the $K I_{B} / f$ term accounts for $1 / \mathrm{f}$ noise (where K is a constant related to device characteristics), and the $\mathrm{I}_{\mathrm{C}}$ term signifies the input-referred collector-current shot noise (which is often disregarded).

Typically, the noise from $r_{b}$ is the predominant factor in $V_{i}(f)$, while the base-current shot noise frequently dominates the input-current noise, $I_{i}^{2}(\mathrm{f})$. Consequently, the equivalent voltage and current noise sources are derived from different noise origins. Therefore, it is a standard assumption that the input voltage and current noise sources in a bipolar transistor are uncorrelated. ${ }^{5}$

