Consider a capacitor, C, in parallel with a resistor, R, as illustrated in Fig. 9.13(a). The corresponding circuit for noise analysis is depicted in Fig. 9.13(b). To calculate the total mean-squared noise voltage across the capacitor, we observe that $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{n} 0}(\mathrm{f})$ is essentially a first-order, low-pass filtered signal with $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{R}}(\mathrm{f})$ as the input. Consequently, we identify that the noise bandwidth is $(\pi / 2) \mathrm{f}_{0}$, as per equation (9.41). Given that the input has a white spectral density, the total output mean-squared value is derived as

$$
\begin{align*}
