#### EXAMPLE 9.8

At a room temperature of $300^{\circ} \mathrm{K}$, what size capacitor is required to achieve a $96-\mathrm{dB}$ dynamic range in an analog circuit with maximum signal levels of 1 V rms?

#### Solution

The tolerable noise level here is 96 dB below 1 V rms, which is

$$
\begin{equation*}
V_{n(\mathrm{rms})}=\frac{1 \mathrm{~V}}{10^{96 / 20}}=15.8 \mu \mathrm{~V} \mathrm{rms} \tag{9.60}
\end{equation*}
$$

Using equation (9.59), we find

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{C}=\frac{\mathrm{kT}}{\mathrm{~V}_{\mathrm{n}(\mathrm{~ms})}^{2}}=16.6 \mathrm{pF} \tag{9.61}
\end{equation*}
$$

Thus, the smallest capacitor size that can be used (without oversampling) is 16.6 pF. This minimum capacitor size dictates the maximum allowable resistance to achieve a specified time constant.

