The input-referred noise of a circuit, if applied to the input of a noiseless copy of the circuit, results in the same output noise as when all the circuit's noise sources are present. This is determined by dividing the observed output noise by the circuit's gain. A method to calculate input-referred noise through analysis or simulation is shown in Fig. 9.15. The output noise $\mathrm{v}_{\text {on(rms) }}$ of the circuit is first measured, then divided by the circuit's mid-band gain to obtain the rms input-referred noise. If the input source is best modeled as a voltage source, it is appropriate to use an input-referred noise voltage defined in terms of the circuit's mid-band small signal voltage gain,

$$
\begin{equation*}
v_{i n(r m s)}=v_{o n(r m s)} / A \tag{9.63}
