Fig. 9.16 illustrates the computation of the input-referred noise for Example 9.9.

#### Solution

The first amplifier has an input-referred noise of $3 \mu \mathrm{~V} / 3=1 \mu \mathrm{~V}_{\mathrm{rms}}$, and the second has an input-referred noise of $6 \mu \mathrm{~V} / 8=0.75 \mu \mathrm{~V}_{\mathrm{rms}}$. First, consider placing the amplifier with a gain of $3 \mathrm{~V} / \mathrm{V}$ first, as shown in Fig. $9.16(a)$. In this case, the total output noise is given by

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{on}(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}=(1 \mu \mathrm{~V})^{2}(3 \cdot 8)^{2}+(0.75 \mu \mathrm{~V})^{2} 8^{2}=0.61 \cdot 10^{-9} \mathrm{~V}^{2} \\
\mathrm{~V}_{\mathrm{on}(\mathrm{rms})}=24.7 \mu \mathrm{~V}_{\mathrm{rms}}
\end{gathered}
$$

The alternative arrangement is depicted in Fig. 9.16(b), resulting in an output noise of

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{on}(\mathrm{rms})}^{2}=(0.75 \mu \mathrm{~V})^{2}(8 \cdot 3)^{2}+(1 \mu \mathrm{~V})^{2} 3^{2}=0.33 \cdot 10^{-9} \mathrm{~V}^{2} \\
\mathrm{~V}_{\mathrm{on}(\mathrm{rms})}=18.2 \mu \mathrm{~V}_{\mathrm{rms}}
\end{gathered}
$$

Clearly, the second arrangement is preferable. The total input-referred noise in this case is

$$
\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{in}(\mathrm{rms})}=18.2 \mu \mathrm{~V}_{\mathrm{rms}} /(3 \cdot 8)=0.76 \mu \mathrm{~V}_{\mathrm{rms}}
$$

Notice that the total input-referred noise is nearly identical to that of the first amplifier alone. This result could also have been obtained by directly input-referring the noise contribution of each amplifier from Fig. 9.16(b).

$$
v_{\text {in(rms) }}=\sqrt{(0.75 \mu \mathrm{~V})^{2}+\frac{(1 \mu \mathrm{~V})^{2}}{8^{2}}}=0.76 \mu \mathrm{~V}_{\mathrm{rms}}
$$

